%             \lambda_{t-1} = 0 , \quad t \geq 1 \cr
%             \frac{\partial L}{\partial v_{1t}} & = -2 \gamma v_{1t} +  \lambda_t = 0 , \quad t \geq 0  \cr }$$
first-order order  conditions \Ep{eq_duop0}
%% and the constraint $q_{1t+1} = q_{1t} + v_{1t} $
%% to take the form
%
%$$ \eqalign{ v_{1t} & = \beta v_{1t+1} + \frac{\beta a_0}{2 \gamma} - \frac{\beta a_1}{\gamma} q_{1t+1} -
%                       \frac{\beta a_1}{2 \gamma} q_{2t+1} \cr
%             q_{t+1} & = q_{1t} + v_{1t} } $$
as components of the following  linear system that confronts the Stackelberg leader firm $2$:
$$ \bmatrix{       1 & 0 & 0 & 0 \cr
                        0 & 1 & 0 & 0 \cr
                        0 & 0 & 1 & 0 \cr
        \frac{\beta a_0}{2 \gamma} & - \frac{\beta a_1}{2 \gamma} & -\frac{\beta a_1}{\gamma} & \beta }
        \bmatrix{ 1 \cr q_{2t+1} \cr q_{1t+1} \cr v_{1t+1} }
        = \bmatrix{ 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 \cr
                          0 & 1 & 0 & 0 \cr
                           0 & 0 & 1 & 1 \cr
                           0 & 0 & 0 & 1 } \bmatrix{ 1 \cr q_{2t} \cr q_{1t} \cr v_{1t} }
        + \bmatrix{ 0 \cr 1 \cr 0 \cr 0 } v_{2t} $$
Time $t$ revenues  of  firm 2 are $\pi_{2t} = a_0 q_{2t} - a_1 q_{2t}^2 - a_1 q_{1t} q_{2t}$ which evidently
equal
$$ z_t' R_1 z_t \equiv \bmatrix{ 1 \cr q_{2t} \cr q_{1t}  }'
   \bmatrix{ 0 & \frac{a_0}{2}& 0 \cr
                   \frac{a_0}{2} & -a_1 & -\frac{a_1}{2}\cr
                   0 & -\frac{a_1}{2} & 0 }
\bmatrix{ 1 \cr q_{2t} \cr q_{1t}  } $$
If we set $Q = \gamma$, then firm 2's period $t$ profits can then be written
$$ y_t' R y_t - Q v_{2t}^2  $$
where $y_t = \bmatrix{ z_t \cr x_t } $ with $x_t = v_{1t}$ and
$R = \bmatrix{ R_1 & 0 \cr 0 & 0 }. $





\section{Recursive formulation}\label{recurstack}%
 To solve  a Stackelberg problem recursively,
 we formulate two Bellman equations in two sets of  state variables.

\subsection{Two Bellman equations}
Given $y_0$, define a feasible set of $(\vec y_1, \vec u_0)$ sequences
% $$
%    \Omega(y_0) = \left\{ (\vec y_1, \vec u_0) : - \sum_{t=0}^\infty \beta^t r(y_t, u_t) > -\infty \ {\rm and} \ y_{t+1} = A y_t + B u_t, \forall t \geq 0 \right\} $$
   $$
   \Omega(y_0) = \left\{ (\vec y_1, \vec u_0) : \ y_{t+1} = A y_t + B u_t, \forall t \geq 0 \right\} $$
%In the definition of $\Omega(y_0)$, $y_0$ is taken as given.
We  express a Stackelberg problem in terms of  two subproblems:

\medskip
\specsec{subproblem 1}

$$   v(y_0) = \max_{(\vec y_1, \vec u_0) \in \Omega(y_0)} - \sum_{t=0}^\infty \beta^t r(y_t, u_t)
   \EQN stacksub1  $$

%\vfil\eject

\medskip
\specsec{subproblem 2}

$$
   w(z_0) = \max_{x_0} v(y_0) \EQN stacksub2 $$

\noindent Working backwards, we solve subproblem 1 first, then subproblem 2.

\subsection{Subproblem 1}
The value function $v(y)$ in  subproblem 1 satisfies the Bellman equation

$$    v(y) = \max_{u, y^*} \left\{ - r(y,u) + \beta v(y^*) \right\} \EQN bell1
$$
where  maximization is subject to
$$     y^* = A y + B u,
  \EQN bell2 $$
and $y^*$ denotes next period's value of $y$.
% The optimal value function $v(y) = - y' P y$ is attained by
% the linear decision rule
% $$ u = - F y $$
% where XXXX
% he linear regulator is
% $$ v(y_0) = -y_0' P y_0
% = {\rm max}_{\{  u_t, y_{t+1}\}_{t=0}^\infty} - \sum_{t=0}^\infty \beta^t
%   \left( y_t' R y_t +   u_t'   Q   u_t \right) \EQN olrp1a $$
% where the maximization is subject to a fixed initial condition for
% $y_0$ and the law of motion\NFootnote{In step 4, we acknowledge that the $x_0$ component
% is {\it not\/} given but is to be chosen by the Stackelberg leader.}
% $$ y_{t+1} = A y_t +   B   u_t . \EQN new30a  $$
 The problem is an instance  of the linear quadratic dynamic programming problem studied in
  chapter \use{dplinear}.  Substituting the (correct) guess  $v(y) = - y'P y$ into  Bellman equation \Ep{bell1}  gives
$$   - y' P y = {\rm max}_{  u, y^*} \left\{ -  y' R y -   u'Q     u - \beta y^{* \prime} P y^* \right\} , $$
which as in chapter \use{dplinear} gives rise to the algebraic matrix Riccati equation
$$    P = R + \beta A' P A - \beta^2 A' P   B (  Q  + \beta   B' P   B)^{-1}   B' P A
    \EQN bell3 $$
and the optimal decision rule  %    the formula for $F$ in the   decision rule
$$    u_t = - F y_t,
  \EQN bell5 $$
where
$$   F = \beta(   Q + \beta   B' P   B)^{-1}  B' P A . \EQN bell4 $$


% Thus, we can solve problem \Ep{new1}, \Ep{new30} by iterating
% to convergence on the difference equation counterpart to the algebraic Riccati equation \Ep{bell3}, or by using
% a faster computational method that emerges as a by-product in
% step 2.  This method is described in Appendix \the\chapternum\use{appBblkstack}.


\subsection{Subproblem 2}

The value function $v(y_0)$ satisfies $v(y) = - y_0' P y_0$ or
$$ v(y_0) = - z_0 ' P_{11} z_0 - 2 x_0' P_{21} z_0 - x_0' P_{22} x_0
     \EQN valuefny $$
where
$$P = \bmatrix{P_{11} & P_{12} \cr P_{21} & P_{22} }.$$
Choose $x_0$ by equating to zero the gradient of $v(y_0)$ with respect to  $x_0$:
$$ - 2 P_{21} z_0 - 2 P_{22} x_0 =0,   $$
which implies that
$$ x_0 = - P_{22}^{-1} P_{21} z_0. \EQN king6x0 $$
We have solved subproblem 2.




\subsection{Representation of Stackelberg plan}

In order to attain an appropriate representation of the Stackelberg leader's history-dependent plan, we will employ what amounts to a version
 of the  ``Big $K$, little $k$'' device encountered in chapter \use{recurpe}  by  distinguishing $z_t$, which depends partly  on decisions $x_t$
of the followers, from $\check z_t$, which does not.  We will use $\check z_t$ and its history $\check z^t = [\check z_t, \check z_{t-1}, \ldots,
\check z_0] $ to describe the sequence of the Stackelberg leader's  decisions  that the Stackelberg follower takes as given.
Thus, we let $\check y_t' = \bmatrix{\check z_t' & \check x_t'}$ with initial condition $\check z_0 = z_0$ given.
We have demonstrated that a Stackelberg plan for $\{u_t\}_{t=0}^\infty$  has a recursive representation
$$ \eqalign{ \check x_0 & = - P_{22}^{-1} P_{21} z_0 \cr
             u_t & = - F \check y_t, \quad t \geq 0 \cr
             \check y_{t+1} & = (A - BF) \check y_t, \quad t \geq 0 . } $$
From this representation we can deduce the sequence of functions $\sigma = \{\sigma_t(\check z^t)\}_{t=0}^\infty$
that comprise a Stackelberg plan.
For convenience, let $\check A \equiv A -  BF$ and partition $\check A$ conformably to the partition
$y_t = \bmatrix{\check z_t \cr \check x_t  }$ as $\bmatrix{\check A_{11} & \check A_{12} \cr \check A_{21} & \check A_{22} } $.
Let $H^0_0 \equiv - P_{22}^{-1} P_{21}$ so that   $\check x_0 = H^0_0 \check z_0$.  Then
iterations on $\check y_{t+1} = \check A \check y_t$ starting from initial condition $\check y_0 = \bmatrix{\check z_0 \cr H^0_0 \check z_0}$
imply that for $t \geq 1$
$$ x_t = \sum_{j=1}^t H_j^t \check z_{t-j} \EQN stackelbergsigma1 $$
where
$$\eqalign{ H^t_1 & = \check A_{21} \cr
            H^t_2 & = \check A_{22} \check A_{21} \cr
           \ \   \vdots \  \  &  \  \ \quad \vdots \cr
           H^t_{t-1} & = \check A_{22}^{t-2} \check A_{21} \cr
            H^t_t & = \check A_{22}^{t-1}(\check A_{21} + \check A_{22} H^0_0 ) . }  $$
%$$\eqalign{ H^t_1 & = \check A_{21} \cr
%            H^t_2 & = \check A_{22} H^{t-1}_1 \cr
%           \ \   \vdots \  \  &  \  \ \quad \vdots \cr
%            H^t_t & = \check A_{22} H^{t-1}_{t-1} . }  $$
An optimal decision rule for the Stackelberg's choice of $u_t$ is
$$ u_t  = - F \check y_t \equiv - \bmatrix{ F_z & F_x \cr } \bmatrix{\check z_t \cr x_t \cr } $$
or
$$   u_t  = - F_z \check z_t - F_x \sum_{j=1}^t H^t_j z_{t-j} = \sigma_t(\check z^t) \EQN  stackelbergsigma2 $$
Representation \Ep{stackelbergsigma2} confirms that whenever $F_x \neq 0$, the typical situation, the time $t$ component $\sigma_t$ of a Stackelberg plan
is {\it history dependent\/}, meaning that the Stackelberg leader's choice $u_t$  depends not just on $\check z_t$ but on components of $\check z^{t-1}$.



\subsection{Backwards-looking representation of $x_t$}

We have noted that equation \Ep{eqn:xlawforward}  portrays $x_t$ as a {\it forward-looking\/} variable that depends on the continuation $\vec u_{t}$ chosen
by the Stackelberg leader. We have now discovered that equation \Ep{stackelbergsigma1} represents $x_t$ as a {\it backward-looking variable} that
depends only on the history of $\check z^t$.  That $x_t$ is both backward and forward  looking reveals essential features of a Stackelberg plan.
The backward looking representation \Ep{stackelbergsigma2} tells how a Stackelberg leader's decisions $u_t$ as functions of histories $\check z^t$ are designed in a way to affect what can be interpreted as a promised value in the form of an  $x_t$ to be delivered by the Stackelberg policy $\sigma$.
We shall use this notion of a promised value often in subsequent chapters.




\subsection{Time  inconsistency}

It is convenient temporarily to proliferate notation by writing history $\check z^t = \check z^t_0$ to emphasize that it starts at $0$ and ends at $t$.
More generally, let $\check z^t_s = [\check z_t, \check z_{t-1}, \ldots, \check z_s] $. A policy $\sigma$ for the Stackelberg leader is the sequence
$$ \sigma =\{\sigma_t(\check z^t_0)\}_{t=0}^\infty .$$   A one-period  continuation of policy $\sigma$ is

$$\sigma_{+1} = \{\sigma_t(\check z^t_0)\}_{t=1}^\infty .$$
Notice that in general
$$ \{ \sigma_1(\check z_0^1), \sigma_2(\check z_0^2), \ldots \} \neq \{\sigma_1(\check z_1^1), \sigma_2(\check z_1^2), \ldots \} .$$
This inequality evidently holds for the representation \Ep{stackelbergsigma2} of the Stackelberg plan derived above.
We conclude that in general a one-period continuation of policy $\sigma$ is not a Stackelberg plan starting from the value of
$\check z_1$ implied by  $\sigma_0(\check z_0)$. A concise way of saying that a one-period continuation of a Stackelberg plan is not a Stackelberg plan is
the statement that  a Stackelberg plan is {\it time inconsistent\/} or {\it dynamically
inconsistent\/}.




\subsection{Recursive representation again}
Recalling that $y_t = \bmatrix{z_t \cr x_t }$, we conclude that, given $z_0$, we also recall that a recursive representation of a Stackelberg plan is
$$\EQNalign{ x_0 & = - P_{22}^{-1} P_{21} z_0 \cr
             u_t & = - F y_t \quad t \geq 0 \cr
             y_{t+1} & = (A - BF) y_t \quad t \geq 0   . \cr}  $$
%
%Equations \Ep{bell5} and \Ep{king6x0} form a  recursive representation of a Stackelberg plan
It is sometimes helpful to adopt the artificial device of imagining that the Stackelberg leader implements the plan with the assistance of
  a sequence of ``continuation Stackelberg leaders.'' These continuation Stackelberg leaders are bound to respect the following rules and
   and   the following timing protocol:\NFootnote{Think of a continuation Stackelberg leader as a computer program that executes the time $t$ component
    of the  plan designed  by the Stackelberg leader at time $0$.}
\smallskip


\item{1.} At time $0$,  a Stackelberg leader takes $z_0$ as given and chooses $x_0$.

\medskip

\item{2.} At times $t \geq 0$,  a continuation Stackelberg  leader takes $(z_t, x_t)$ as given and chooses $ (u_t, z_{t+1}, x_{t+1}) $.

\medskip



\noindent Notice how we have distinguished the problems confronting
  continuation Stackelberg leaders who choose at times $t \geq 0$ and a Stackelberg leader who
chooses at time $t=0$.
In this timing protocol, the  forward looking vector $x_t$ that obeys \Ep{eqn:xlawforward} is part of the  state vector confronting
a continuation Stackelberg leader at times $t \geq 0$ but not  part of the state confronting the Stackelberg leader at time $t=0$.  It is  presented to a continuation leader
at time $t \geq 0$ as a promise to be kept.  The time $t$ continuation leader delivers $x_t$  by choosing $u_t, z_{t+1}, x_{t+1}$.\NFootnote{See
exercise \the\chapternum.2 for a  timing protocol that builds in time consistency.}




\subsection{Time inconsistency again}
We can use the  two subproblems in section \use{recurstack} to glean further insights about  the time inconsistency of the optimal decisions of a Stackelberg leader.
In the recursive representation of
 a Stackelberg plan, different state variables confront a Stackelberg leader at $t=0$, on the one hand, and continuation Stackelberg leaders at dates $t \geq 0$, on the other.
At $t =0$, the leader faces $z_0$ as a state vector and  chooses the forward looking
vector $x_0$ as well as the forward looking vector $x_1$ that will confront the continuation
leader at time $1$.  At dates $t \geq 0$,  a continuation leader confronts the state vector $x_t$  as  values promised at time $t-1$ that must
be confirmed at $t$.\NFootnote{Another manifestation of time-inconsistency is that $\mu_{xt}$ is zero at $t=0$ and different
from zero at $t \geq  1$.}
%The multiplier $\mu_{xt}$  accounts for how the optimal plan used $u_{t+j}, j \geq 0$ to influence the followers' choice of
%$x_s$  at dates $s <  t$ and assures  that the Stackelberg leader confirm those expectations.


Define $\vec a_1$ as the continuation of the sequence $\vec a_0$. A
 Stackelberg plan is a triple $(\vec u_0, \vec x_0, \vec z_1)$ that solves the Stackelberg problem starting from a given $z_0$.

\specsec{Time inconsistency:}
  A concise way
to say that a Stackelberg plan is {\it time inconsistent\/} is to note that a continuation of a Stackelberg plan is not
a Stackelberg plan. Why? Because $x_1$ does not solve subproblem 2 at initial condition $z_1$ generated by a Stackelberg plan.
\index{continuation!of a sequence}%
\index{continuation!of a Stackelberg plan}%




\specsec{Remark about shadow prices:}
From chapter \use{dplinear}, recall the formula $\mu_t = P y_t$ for the vector of
shadow prices $\mu_t = \bmatrix{ \mu_{zt} \cr \mu_{xt} }$ on the time $t$  transition equations.
The shadow price $\mu_{xt}$ evidently equals
$$ \mu_{xt} = P_{21} z_t + P_{22} x_t.   \EQN eqnmux $$
So  \Ep{king6x0} is equivalent with
$$ \mu_{x0} = 0 . \EQN mu0condition  $$
The Lagrange multiplier $\mu_{xt}$ measures the cost to the leader at $t \geq 0$
of confirming expectations about its time $t$ action that the followers held
at dates $s < t$.
Setting
$\mu_{x0}=0$ reflects the situation that at time $0$ there are no prior expectations to confirm.  But
when $\mu_{xt} \neq 0 $ for $ t \geq 1$, it indicates that  it is costly to the original (time $0$) Stackelberg leader for a time $t$ continuation leader to confirm  the followers'  expectations about
 the leader's time $s \geq t$ actions.
 %The  Stackelberg leader takes these costs into account when at time $0$  it weighs the costs and benefits
%of using its choice of $ u_{t}, t \geq 1$ to influence $\{x_s\}_{s=0}^{t-1}$.

